@n3nash 
You mean if there is a lot of inserts in the following incremental upsert, the file size can grow larger. Correct me if I'm wrong.
If I using spark streaming to do the incremental upserts with MAX_PARQUET_FILE_SIZE setting to 256MB and  PARQUET_SMALL_FILE_LIMIT_BYTES setting to 128MB, what's the recommended spark duration and hoodie configuration?

@n3nash 
2 cores per executors. But we tried different configurations such that 1 to 4 cores per executors.

Is there any special configuration need to be done from hudi config side for large scale ?

@MohitShiv At the moment, it is recommended to use Hudi with 1 core per executor. Here are some details around why : https://github.com/uber/hudi/issues/254 and the task to document it https://github.com/uber/hudi/issues/479. You can always increase the number of executors (just like you were increasing the number of cores). 
I'm not sure what you mean by large scale ? Could you share some information about 1) What's your batch size 2) How frequently are you running it 3) What's the bottleneck you see in running the job ?

We can then analyze the problem with the job and tune the configurations accordingly.

In `com/uber/hoodie/hadoop/realtime/AbstractRealtimeRecordReader.java`, before adding partition columns to Schema, check if partition columns length first as follow: 
`    

    String partitionColumns = jobConf.get("partition_columns","");

    List<String> partitioningFields = Arrays.stream(partitionColumns.split(",")).collect(Collectors.toList());

    if(partitionColumns.length() > 0){
      writerSchema = addPartitionFields(writerSchema, partitioningFields);
    }`

this basically amounts to not marking success (not exactly, since totalRecords needs to be bumped up), for implicit indexes

```
if (!hoodieTable.getIndex().isImplicitWithStorage()) {
        writeStatus.markSuccess(record, recordMetadata);
      }
```

@ovj whats going to break for your subclassed WriteStatuses if we make this change? I really want to fix this.. 

